# React and Next.js Rules

## General
- Use TypeScript in strict mode.
- Prefer functional components.
- Keep components small and focused.
- Use explicit prop typing.
- Prefer clear and descriptive names for props, handlers and utilities.

## Organization
- Organize by feature/domain first.
- Inside each feature, separate concerns when useful:
  - components
  - hooks
  - services
  - mappers
  - types
  - validation
  - tests

## Components
- Prefer composition over overly configurable components.
- Avoid components with too many props.
- Extract subcomponents when responsibilities diverge.
- Keep JSX readable.
- Move complex logic outside render.
- Use named handlers such as handleClick, handleSubmit and handleChange.

## Hooks
- Use custom hooks to encapsulate reusable stateful logic.
- Do not create hooks just to move trivial code around.
- Keep hooks focused and well named.
- Avoid hooks that mix unrelated responsibilities.

## State and Async
- Keep fetching logic outside purely presentational components.
- Prefer typed service functions for external calls.
- Always model loading, empty and error states explicitly.
- Keep server state and UI state conceptually separated.

## Next.js
- Use server/client boundaries intentionally.
- Default to server-side capabilities where appropriate.
- Use client components only when interactivity, browser APIs or local state require them.
- Keep route handlers, server actions and server-only modules clearly separated from client code.
- Respect App Router conventions when using App Router.

## Styling
- Use Tailwind consistently when that is the project standard.
- Prefer class composition helpers like cn(), clsx() or cva() when class composition grows.
- Keep className readable and maintainable.

## Accessibility
- Use semantic elements first.
- Ensure keyboard interaction works.
- Use aria-* correctly, not excessively.

## Testing
- Test critical user flows.
- Test hooks and utilities separately when logic is non-trivial.
